id":-1},"b98d4d2a-2f2e-4bb5-8c1f-04fa7586f31f","ssn:System",[135,69,178,71],"Sensor Platform","entities/ssn_system",{"uuid":181,"title":182,"slug":183},"e04906c9-3790-497f-850e-bba1a730097e","Documentation","index",{"id":185,"title":186,"description":187,"author":16,"date":17,"published":18,"slug":188,"uuid":-1,"children":189},"fedcee5c-aef3-41d6-975a-9dbea14ffd68","RDF Ontologies in SDL","A reference guide to the RDF namespaces and key classes used across the Scientific Data Layer (SDL).","ontologies",[190,194],{"id":191,"title":192,"slug":193,"uuid":-1},"b3f22181-62f0-4676-aab3-34afb972d514","DoCO (Document Components Ontology) Classes","ontologies/DoCO",{"id":195,"title":196,"slug":197,"uuid":-1},"5d1ed897-c4e3-49d3-8d86-28b41540fb7e","Detailed Descriptions of DoCO Classes","ontologies/doco_class_details",{"title":199,"published":200,"slug":201,"uuid":-1},"URI namespaces",false,"uris",{"uuid":203,"title":204,"slug":205,"children":206},"b73fe1e6-3e7e-456a-a5e3-70857a77be3c","SDL User Guide","user",[207,211,219,224],{"title":208,"description":209,"author":16,"date":17,"published":18,"slug":210,"uuid":-1},"Semantic Content Blocks","Learn how to create, edit, and annotate semantic blocks within the SDL platform.","user/semantic_editing",{"id":212,"title":213,"author":16,"tags":214,"version":61,"slug":218,"uuid":-1},"d23e7492-469b-4fa5-bbde-e3f320c6a62c","Scientific Data Layer â€” User FAQ",[215,182,216,217],"FAQ","Help","User Support","user/user_faq",{"id":220,"title":221,"description":222,"author":16,"date":17,"published":18,"slug":223,"uuid":-1},"709d8328-5fe5-4c21-9032-7c75536d4576","User Guide","A comprehensive guide for users to navigate and utilize the Scientific Data Layer (SDL) platform.","user/user_guide",{"title":225,"id":226,"description":227,"author":16,"date":17,"published":18,"slug":228,"uuid":-1},"Workspaces & Navigation","345d45b3-b503-46a9-95bc-3e0c2549e4c5","An overview of SDL workspaces and how to navigate the platform efficiently.","user/workspaces_navigation"],"uses":{}},null,{"type":"data","data":[{"post":1},{"content":2,"meta":3},"\u003Cblockquote>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Disclaimer:\u003C/strong> Many of the features described in this guide are still in planning or development. Your instance may not yet support all described functionality.\u003C/p>\n\u003C/blockquote>\n\u003Cp>Ontologies are a core part of the Scientific Data Layer (SDL), enabling semantic interoperability, structured knowledge representation, and reasoning across services.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>This guide covers how ontologies are used, loaded, aligned, and extended within SDL.\u003C/p>\n\u003Csection>\u003Ch2 id=\"purpose-of-ontologies-in-sdl\">\u003Ca href=\"#purpose-of-ontologies-in-sdl\">Purpose of Ontologies in SDL\u003C/a>\u003C/h2>\u003Cp>The \u003Cspan class=\"hover:cursor-help border-b border-dotted sdl-abbr\">SDL\u003C/span> relies on \u003Cspan class=\"hover:cursor-help border-b border-dotted sdl-abbr\">RDF\u003C/span> and \u003Cspan class=\"hover:cursor-help border-b border-dotted sdl-abbr\">OWL\u003C/span> ontologies to model resources and their relationships.\nIn \u003Cspan class=\"hover:cursor-help border-b border-dotted sdl-abbr\">RDF\u003C/span>, a resource is described using one or more assertions (statements) about it.\nA Resources can be assigned one or more classes in \u003Cspan class=\"hover:cursor-help border-b border-dotted sdl-abbr\">RDF\u003C/span> vocabularies or \u003Cspan class=\"hover:cursor-help border-b border-dotted sdl-abbr\">OWL\u003C/span> ontologies.\nAdditionally it can also have properties, providing additional context.\u003C/p>\u003Cpre>\u003Ccode class=\"language-turtle\">&#x3C;http://example.org/sensors/LI-8250> a ssn:Sensor .\n\u003C/code>\u003C/pre>\u003Cp>The example above is a single \u003Cspan class=\"hover:cursor-help border-b border-dotted sdl-abbr\">RDF\u003C/span> statement (a \"triple\") written in Turtle syntax.\nEvery triple has a \u003Cem>Subject\u003C/em>, \u003Cem>Predicate\u003C/em> and \u003Cem>Object\u003C/em>: the \u003Cem>Subject\u003C/em> identifies the resource, and the \u003Cem>Predicate\u003C/em> links it to another \u003Cem>Object\u003C/em>.\u003C/p>\u003Cp>The next example adds a second assertion about the same resource:\u003C/p>\u003Cpre>\u003Ccode class=\"language-turtle\">&#x3C;http://example.org/sensors/LI-8250> a ssn:Sensor .\n&#x3C;http://example.org/sensors/LI-8250> a dcat:Resource .\n\u003C/code>\u003C/pre>\u003Cp>The token \u003Ccode>a\u003C/code> is a Turtle shorthand for \u003Cspan>rdf:type\u003C/span>, which asserts that the \u003Cem>Subject\u003C/em> is an instance of the \u003Cem>Object\u003C/em> class.\nFrom these two assertions, we can see that \u003Ccode>&#x3C;http://example.org/sensors/LI-8250>\u003C/code> is simultaneously an instance of both \u003Cspan>ssn:Sensor\u003C/span> and \u003Cspan>dcat:Resource\u003C/span>.\nIn \u003Cspan class=\"hover:cursor-help border-b border-dotted sdl-abbr\">RDF\u003C/span>, a resource may belong to multiple classes.\nThis can be used by applications, reasoners, and agents to combine semantics from multiple ontologies.\u003C/p>\u003Cp>Ontologies provide the semantic backbone for:\u003C/p>\u003Csection>\u003Ch3 id=\"resource-typing\">\u003Ca href=\"#resource-typing\">Resource typing\u003C/a>\u003C/h3>\u003Cp>Resources within the SDL are typed using different classes from multiple vocabularies and ontologies, e.g., \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">ssn:Sensor\u003C/span>, \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">dcat:Dataset\u003C/span>, \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">prov:Activity\u003C/span>.\u003C/p>\u003C/section>\u003Csection>\u003Ch3 id=\"data-validation\">\u003Ca href=\"#data-validation\">Data validation\u003C/a>\u003C/h3>\u003Cp>using SHACL and reasoning\u003C/p>\u003C/section>\u003Csection>\u003Ch3 id=\"ui-rendering\">\u003Ca href=\"#ui-rendering\">UI rendering\u003C/a>\u003C/h3>\u003Cp>via \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">rdfs:Class\u003C/span> and \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">sh:property\u003C/span> definitions\u003C/p>\u003C/section>\u003Csection>\u003Ch3 id=\"search-and-discovery\">\u003Ca href=\"#search-and-discovery\">Search and discovery\u003C/a>\u003C/h3>\u003Cp>via class-based filters\u003C/p>\u003C/section>\u003Csection>\u003Ch3 id=\"automated-workflows-and-provenance-tracking\">\u003Ca href=\"#automated-workflows-and-provenance-tracking\">Automated workflows and provenance tracking\u003C/a>\u003C/h3>\u003C/section>\u003C/section>\n\u003Csection>\u003Ch2 id=\"supported-ontologies\">\u003Ca href=\"#supported-ontologies\">Supported Ontologies\u003C/a>\u003C/h2>\u003Cp>SDL integrates a range of standard and domain-specific ontologies:\u003C/p>\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>DCAT v3\u003C/strong> Catalogs and datasets\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>SSN/SOSA\u003C/strong> Sensors, systems, observations\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>PROV-O\u003C/strong> Provenance of data and workflows\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>DoCO\u003C/strong> Document components (for semantic content blocks)\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>SKOS\u003C/strong> Controlled vocabularies\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>SHACL\u003C/strong> Shape constraints for validation\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\u003Cp>Custom or local ontologies can be loaded to support specific domains.\u003C/p>\u003C/section>\n\u003Csection>\u003Ch2 id=\"ontology-management\">\u003Ca href=\"#ontology-management\">Ontology Management\u003C/a>\u003C/h2>\u003Cp>Ontologies are loaded into the RDF store under a dedicated graph (e.g., \u003Ccode>http://example.org/ontologies\u003C/code>).\u003C/p>\u003Cp>You can manage ontologies using:\u003C/p>\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>The \u003Cstrong>Repository Service\u003C/strong> (\u003Ccode>POST /repository/resources\u003C/code>) to upload \u003Ccode>.ttl\u003C/code> or \u003Ccode>.jsonld\u003C/code> files\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>A \u003Cstrong>designated admin UI\u003C/strong> (planned)\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Programmatic loading during deployment/configuration\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\u003C/section>\n\u003Csection>\u003Ch2 id=\"aligning-data-with-ontologies\">\u003Ca href=\"#aligning-data-with-ontologies\">Aligning Data with Ontologies\u003C/a>\u003C/h2>\u003Cp>Each resource is annotated with \u003Ccode>@type\u003C/code> and optionally \u003Ccode>@context\u003C/code> to associate it with ontology terms.\u003C/p>\u003Cp>Example:\u003C/p>\u003Cpre>\u003Ccode class=\"language-json\">{\n  \"@type\": \"ssn:Sensor\",\n  \"rdfs:label\": \"LI-8250 CO2 Analyzer\",\n  \"sosa:hosts\": { \"@id\": \"platform:chamber01\" }\n}\n\u003C/code>\u003C/pre>\u003Cpre>\u003Ccode class=\"language-turtle\">@prefix ssn: &#x3C;http://www.w3.org/ns/ssn/> .\n@prefix sosa: &#x3C;http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/> .\n@prefix rdfs: &#x3C;http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .\n@prefix platform: &#x3C;http://example.org/platform/> .\n\n&#x3C;http://example.org/sensors/LI-8250> a ssn:Sensor ;\n  rdfs:label \"LI-8250 CO2 Analyzer\" ;\n  sosa:hosts platform:chamber01 .\n\u003C/code>\u003C/pre>\u003Cp>Validation and reasoning can check for consistency with the ontology definition.\u003C/p>\u003C/section>\n\u003Csection>\u003Ch2 id=\"ui-integration\">\u003Ca href=\"#ui-integration\">UI Integration\u003C/a>\u003C/h2>\u003Cp>SDL uses ontologies to drive the UI dynamically:\u003C/p>\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>Forms are generated based on \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">sh:NodeShape\u003C/span>\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Labels, descriptions, ranges are extracted from \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">rdfs:label\u003C/span>, \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">rdfs:comment\u003C/span>, \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">sh:datatype\u003C/span>, etc.\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Type-aware rendering of content blocks (e.g., data block vs. reference block)\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\u003Cp>This enables a flexible interface that adjusts to new types without hardcoding.\u003C/p>\u003C/section>\n\u003Csection>\u003Ch2 id=\"extending-ontologies\">\u003Ca href=\"#extending-ontologies\">Extending Ontologies\u003C/a>\u003C/h2>\u003Cp>Users can:\u003C/p>\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>Import new vocabularies\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Define subclasses of known types\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Attach UI metadata using \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">sdl:uiTemplate\u003C/span>, \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">sh:group\u003C/span>, or \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">skos:note\u003C/span>\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Reference external ontologies (via \u003Cspan class=\"mr-1 px-2 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-lg\">owl:imports\u003C/span>)\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\u003Cp>Custom extensions can be maintained in dedicated named graphs.\u003C/p>\u003C/section>\n\u003Csection>\u003Ch2 id=\"planned-features\">\u003Ca href=\"#planned-features\">Planned Features\u003C/a>\u003C/h2>\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>Ontology browser UI\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Version control for vocabularies\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>SPIN/SHACL reasoning support\u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Context-aware autocompletion during semantic editing\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\u003Cp>Ontology integration ensures that SDL remains modular, extensible, and aligned with FAIR principles for data management and reuse.\u003C/p>\u003C/section>",{"id":4,"title":5,"description":6,"author":7,"date":8,"published":9,"toc":10},"16d67c2e-0382-497f-9616-f850f31362a5","Ontology Integration","How ontologies are used and integrated within the Scientific Data Layer (SDL).","SDL Team","2025-06-25",true,[11,18,23,27,31,36,41,45,49,53,57,62],{"value":12,"href":13,"depth":14,"numbering":15,"parent":17},"Purpose of Ontologies in SDL","#purpose-of-ontologies-in-sdl",2,[16,16],1,"section",{"value":19,"href":20,"depth":21,"numbering":22,"parent":17},"Resource typing","#resource-typing",3,[16,16,16],{"value":24,"href":25,"depth":21,"numbering":26,"parent":17},"Data validation","#data-validation",[16,16,14],{"value":28,"href":29,"depth":21,"numbering":30,"parent":17},"UI rendering","#ui-rendering",[16,16,21],{"value":32,"href":33,"depth":21,"numbering":34,"parent":17},"Search and discovery","#search-and-discovery",[16,16,35],4,{"value":37,"href":38,"depth":21,"numbering":39,"parent":17},"Automated workflows and provenance tracking","#automated-workflows-and-provenance-tracking",[16,16,40],5,{"value":42,"href":43,"depth":14,"numbering":44,"parent":17},"Supported Ontologies","#supported-ontologies",[16,14],{"value":46,"href":47,"depth":14,"numbering":48,"parent":17},"Ontology Management","#ontology-management",[16,21],{"value":50,"href":51,"depth":14,"numbering":52,"parent":17},"Aligning Data with Ontologies","#aligning-data-with-ontologies",[16,35],{"value":54,"href":55,"depth":14,"numbering":56,"parent":17},"UI Integration","#ui-integration",[16,40],{"value":58,"href":59,"depth":14,"numbering":60,"parent":17},"Extending Ontologies","#extending-ontologies",[16,61],6,{"value":63,"href":64,"depth":14,"numbering":65,"parent":17},"Planned Features","#planned-features",[16,66],7],"uses":{"params":["slug"]}}]}
